istic forenames:  Chinese Young, Sang, Jae, Jong, Jung, Sung, Yong, Kyung, Seung, Dong, Kwang, Myung.","English: topographic name for someone who lived near a meadow or a patch of arable land, Middle English <i>lee</i>, <i>lea</i>, from Old English <i>lēa</i>, dative case (used after a preposition) of <i>lēah</i>, which originally meant ‘wood or glade’.","English: habitational name from any of the many places in England named with Old English <i>lēah</i> ‘wood, glade’, including Lee in Buckinghamshire, Essex, Hampshire, Kent, and Shropshire, and Lea in Cheshire, Derbyshire, Herefordshire, Lancashire, Lincolnshire, and Wiltshire."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Alice Leigh was born in 1360, in Cheshire, England, United Kingdom. She married John Mompesson in 1385, in Stockwell, Surrey, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died in 1388, in her hometown, at the age of 28."},"et":{"1360–1388":"1360–1388","1360–1411":"1360–1411","1388–1413":"1388–1413","1413":"1413","Abt 1388":"umbes 1388","1411":"1411","1388":"1388","1385":"1385","1360":"1360","Stockwell, Cheshire, England":"Stockwell, Surrey, England","Stockwell, Cheshire, E